50|$|Andrew Carnegie {{had promised}} {{in a letter}} to Mr Thomas Jeffrey of Airdrie Savings Bank an amount of money equaling £1,000 (being <b>half</b> of <b>the</b> <b>money</b> {{required}} to build a new library) so long as a piece of land was acquired and <b>the</b> other <b>half</b> of <b>the</b> <b>money</b> was raised locally. On receiving this guarantee, a public appeal was launched on 13 June 1892 for funds, and by October 1892 more than £1,000 had been raised. With more than £2,000, plans were drawn up to build the new Library on Anderson Street.|$|R
