2500|$|Edward Ballard, who {{financed the}} hotel's improvements, {{began his career}} as a bowling alley worker in the hotel, but made a fortune by {{operating}} an illegal gambling business in the area. Ballard also owned several nationally-recognized touring circuses, including the Hagenbeck-Wallace Circus. Between 1918 and 1919, while the hotel was being refurbished, it served as a U.S. Army hospital for wounded soldiers returning from World War I. Lillian Wexford and [...] Lieutenant Charles Cooper fell in love during his stay at the hotel-hospital. The Rexfords divorced in 1922, and Lillian [...] sold the property to Ballard for $1 million in 1923. <b>Half</b> <b>the</b> <b>money</b> repaid the debt owed to Ballard; Lillian she kept the remainder.|$|E
